In the constructor `explicit DDR5SPD(std::span<const uint8_t> spdBytes);`, I deep copied the input `std::span<const uint8_t> spdBytes` into a member vector `spdBytes_`.
So I think the class DDR5SPD owns the SPD data by itself. Should not have life cycle issue.
```
DDR5SPD::DDR5SPD(std::span<const uint8_t> spdBytes) :
    spdBytes_(spdBytes.begin(), spdBytes.end())    <--- deep copy here
{
    spd_ = reinterpret_cast<DDR5Fields*>(spdBytes_.data());
}
```

"return std::make_unique<DDR5SPD>(spdBytes);" won't work because the constructor is private. And the `make_unique` cannot access private constructor.
I found 2 alternatives to solve this.
- Passing a `new` instance to unique_ptr constructor. 
- Make the constructor public while add a private struct variable as input argument. So user can't use this constructor because they can't access private struct. https://seanmiddleditch.github.io/enabling-make-unique-with-private-constructors/

I chose the former one because it's more cleaner.

-------------------------------------------------

> per our coding standard, new and delete shouldn't be used anymore.

I think the reason that `new` is forbidden because it may cause memory issue if we forget to delete it.
However directly passes the `new` instance into unique_ptr won't have this kind of issue.

```
void foo(int* input_ptr) {
    auto uptr = std::unique_ptr<int>{input_ptr};
    cout << "uptr = " << (uint64_t) uptr.get() << ", *uptr = " << *uptr << endl;
}
int main() {
    int* ptr = new int(10);
    cout << "ptr  = " << (uint64_t) ptr << ", *ptr  = " << *ptr << endl;
    foo(ptr);
    cout << "ptr  = " << (uint64_t) ptr << ", *ptr  = " << *ptr << endl;
    delete ptr;
    return 0;
}
```
